result.content: # Euroscope Installation Euroscope is a very powerful software used for the Air Traffic Controller (ATC) on the Vatsim network. It is important to setup the software correctly, before controlling. It will take some time until you feel familiar with it. # Installation Downloads - both are required Visual C++ Redistributable x86: https://aka.ms/vs/17/release/vc_redist.x86.exe EuroScope Version 3.2.3.2: https://euroscope.hu/install/EuroScopeSetup.3.2.3.2.msi ## The currently tested and approved EuroScope version is 3.2.3.2. There are newer versions (3.2.4+), however these versions all have been causing various issues and are not approved for usage in Germany. Versions 3.2.3 and older will also not work due to new VATSIM authentication requirements. For further information check your respective NAV team's announcements. Please install the software into a directory of your choice. # Audio for Vatsim (AfV) To use voice communication you have to install the additional software Audio for Vatsim. After that, run the software and check the settings for your audio devices and enter your ID and password. While controlling, it's recommended to run the software as administrator to work correctly in the background. For push to talk we recommend the left ctrl (Strg) button at your keyboard. If you have a primary frequency set in Euroscope, AfV will set it's frequency automatically after clicking on "connect". # Initial Setup After installing the software you still need the sectorfile, where you get all local data from you need for controlling. Additional to the sectorfile we offer a variety of files and plugins pre installed, so that this package is ready to use for you. You can download the different packages for each FIR at files.aero-nav.com/EDXX. Download the package and create a folder anywhere you like (recommended at C:\Users\me\Documents\EuroScope). For a better overview we recommend to name the folder according to the FIR where the data is coming from (EDGG, EDMM or EDWW). Copy all provided data into the folder in the same structure as download, as it will not work otherwise! Select a Profile: After you've done the above steps, you can open Euroscope and you are prompted to select a profile (.prf file). Choose one of the provided ones and you are ready to use Euroscope and all it's features. Different views and airports are already predefined. Therefore you have to click on "OPEN SCT" in the green colored menu bar and select one of the listed .asr files or load one of other provided files via the "Open ... " menu. If you would like to open a different profile over the time or you have some problems with different views (e.g. you have choosen the "wrong" profile), it's highly recommended to disable the "Auto load last profile on startup" and "Auto save profile on exit" items to always select the profile manually. You can find these options at OTHER SET at the top menu bar of Euroscope. ## Login as Observer You can always login as observer (OBS). Open your profile of choice and click on "Connect" at the upper left corner. As Callsign we suggest to use XX_OBS with XX replaced by your initials (the_OBS at the end is required). Enter your ID and password, check your rating (probably observer), choose your server and you can connect to Vatsim. Listen to the Frequency: In order to listen to other controllers, you have to open AfV and click on connect thereafter. Then you need to click on the small "+" to enter the station Login into the search window you would like to listen to (e.g. EDDF_S_TWR). You will get a selection of frequencies to listen to. Click on RX and you will hear the controller and the pilots on that frequency. Select the active airport and runways: It is also recommended to activate the airport and it's select runways. Only if the airport is selected, you can see information in the different lists (e.g. you will only see Frankfurt departures in the departliste list, if EDDF is activated). Simply click on the runway symbol at the menu bar at the top, activate the airport for ARR and DEP, chose the runway and you can see everything the controller sees as well. Reset visual point: If you can't see any traffic as Observer even if there should be some, it might be your visual point is to far away from the airport you are looking at. To reposition your center of view, enter .vis into the command line at the bottom and click into the scope. Your center of view is repositioned thereafter. The image appears to be a screenshot from an air traffic control simulation or radar display. It shows a dark background with various lines and symbols representing runways, taxiways, and aircraft positions. 

Key elements include:
- A central runway marked with dashed lines.
- Several aircraft identified by labels such as "DAL 1234" and "UAL 5678," each with associated data like altitude and speed.
- A control panel at the top of the screen displaying information such as flight numbers, altitudes, speeds, and headings.
- A text log at the bottom of the screen, likely showing recent communications or system messages.

The display is used to monitor and manage aircraft movements on the ground and in the airspace around an airport.

The image shows a screenshot of a software interface, specifically the "Sector Menu" of a program called EuroScope. The menu lists various options related to air traffic control sectors, including downloading sector files, opening files, saving files, and loading different types of data such as ICAO airlines, airports, aircraft, and navigation data. The top of the interface displays identifiers "EDDF_PHX_TWR" and "DLH7JA" along with a timestamp "18:52:30". The "Open ..." option is highlighted with a red box.

The image shows a screenshot of a software interface, specifically a settings menu. The menu includes various options related to profiles, settings, and configurations. Two options are highlighted with a red box: "Auto load last profile on startup" and "Auto save profile on exit." The menu also includes options for saving and loading profiles, general settings, display settings, system messages, and other configurations. The interface appears to be related to a navigation or control system, possibly for aviation or simulation purposes, as indicated by terms like "airports/runways," "sector ownership setup," and "aircraft around planes." The top part of the interface shows a time stamp (18:51:21) and other numerical indicators.

The image is a screenshot of a software interface used for managing transceivers in a virtual air traffic control environment, specifically for VATSIM (Virtual Air Traffic Simulation Network). The interface displays the following elements:

1. **Top Section:**
   - Buttons for "Disconnect" and "Settings."
   - The current transceiver source is "Controller Client."
   - The transceiver count is 1.
   - The ATIS (Automatic Terminal Information Service) source is "Text to Speech from FSD."

2. **Middle Section:**
   - A list of transceivers with their respective frequencies and statuses:
     - **XX_OBS:** Frequency 199.998, status RX (Receive) and TX (Transmit).
     - **EDDF_S_TWR:** Frequency 119.900, status RX (Receive) and XC (Cross Coupled).
     - **EDDF_W_TWR:** Frequency 124.850, status RX (Receive) and XC (Cross Coupled).
   - A button with a "+" symbol, likely for adding new transceivers.

3. **Right Section:**
   - Information about the audio settings for VATSIM V1.5.7.
   - Radio status: TX (Transmit) and RX (Receive).
   - Last received frequency and callsign are not available.
   - An area for "Additional Airport Transceivers" with options to "Add," "Remove All," and "Map."
   - A note indicating that additional transceivers should only be used in exceptional circumstances and advising to contact the division's facility engineer for radio coverage issues.

Overall, the interface is designed to manage and monitor multiple transceivers for virtual air traffic control operations.

The image shows a software interface for connecting to VATSIM (Virtual Air Traffic Simulation Network). The interface is divided into several sections:

1. **Select Connection Mode**: A dropdown menu to choose the connection mode, currently set to "Direct to VATSIM".
2. **Server Connection**: 
   - **Callsign**: Input field with "PGX_OBS".
   - **Real Name**: Input field with "Max Mustermann".
   - **Certificate**: Input field with "123456".
   - **Password**: Input field for a 4-digit password.
   - **Facility**: Dropdown menu set to "Observer".
   - **Rating**: Dropdown menu set to "Observer".
   - **Server**: Dropdown menu set to "GERMANY".
   - **Connect to VATSIM**: Checkbox.
   - **Save Profile** and **Delete Profile**: Buttons for profile management.
3. **Logoff Time**: Input field for logoff time in minutes.
4. **INFO line 1-4**: Input fields for additional information.
5. **Range**: Slider set to 100.
6. **Status**: Status indicator.
7. **Proxy Connection**: 
   - **Server**: Input field set to "localhost".
   - **Status**: Indicator showing "Proxy server is running".
   - **Start Proxy Server** and **Stop Proxy Server**: Buttons to control the proxy server.
8. **Simulator Server**: 
   - **Scenario**: Input field.
   - **Publish simulation data**: Checkbox.
9. **Logging and Playback**: 
   - **Logfile**: Input field with a file path.
   - **Start logging** and **Stop logging**: Buttons to control logging.
   - **Playback**: Controls for playback with buttons for play, pause, stop, and various speed adjustments.

The interface is designed for users to connect to VATSIM, manage their connection settings, and control logging and playback of simulation data.

chunks.pageContent: Euroscope Installation Euroscope is a very powerful software used for the Air Traffic Controller (ATC) on the Vatsim network. It is important to setup the software correctly, before controlling. It will take some time until you feel familiar with it. Installation Downloads - both are required Visual C++ Redistributable x86: https://aka.ms/vs/17/release/vc_redist.x86.exe EuroScope Version 3.2.3.2: https://euroscope.hu/install/EuroScopeSetup.3.2.3.2.msi The currently tested and approved EuroScope version is 3.2.3.2. There are newer versions (3.2.4+), however these versions all have been causing various issues and are not approved for usage in Germany. Versions 3.2.3 and older will also not work due to new VATSIM authentication requirements. For further information check your respective NAV team's announcements. Please install the software into a directory of your choice.

Frankfurt Tower - Radar View 'The image appears to be a screenshot from an air traffic control simulation or radar display. It shows a dark background with various lines and symbols representing runways, taxiways, and aircraft positions. 

Key elements include:
- A central runway marked with dashed lines.
- Several aircraft identified by labels such as "DAL 1234" and "UAL 5678," each with associated data like altitude and speed.
- A control panel at the top of the screen displaying information such as flight numbers, altitudes, speeds, and headings.
- A text log at the bottom of the screen, likely showing recent communications or system messages.

The display is used to monitor and manage aircraft movements on the ground and in the airspace around an airport.' Audio for Vatsim (AfV) To use voice communication you have to install the additional software Audio for Vatsim. After that, run the software and check the settings for your audio devices and enter your ID and password. While controlling, it's recommended to run the software as administrator to work correctly in the background. For push to talk we recommend the left ctrl (Strg) button at your keyboard. If you have a primary frequency set in Euroscope, AfV will set it's frequency automatically after clicking on "connect". Initial Setup After installing the software you still need the sectorfile, where you get all local data from you need for controlling. Additional to the sectorfile we offer a variety of files and plugins pre installed, so that this package is ready to use for you. You can download the different packages for each FIR at files.aero-nav.com/EDXX. Download the package and create a folder anywhere you like (recommended at C:\Users\me\Documents\EuroScope). For a better overview we recommend to name the folder according to the FIR where the data is coming from (EDGG, EDMM or EDWW). Copy all provided data into the folder in the same structure as download, as it will not work otherwise!

Select a Profile: After you've done the above steps, you can open Euroscope and you are prompted to select a profile (.prf file). Choose one of the provided ones and you are ready to use Euroscope and all it's features. Different views and airports are already predefined. Therefore you have to click on "OPEN SCT" in the green colored menu bar and select one of the listed .asr files or load one of other provided files via the "Open ... " menu. Open a new .asr file for different views 'The image shows a screenshot of a software interface, specifically the "Sector Menu" of a program called EuroScope. The menu lists various options related to air traffic control sectors, including downloading sector files, opening files, saving files, and loading different types of data such as ICAO airlines, airports, aircraft, and navigation data. The top of the interface displays identifiers "EDDF_PHX_TWR" and "DLH7JA" along with a timestamp "18:52:30". The "Open ..." option is highlighted with a red box.' Disable "auto load" and "auto save" 'The image shows a screenshot of a software interface, specifically a settings menu. The menu includes various options related to profiles, settings, and configurations. Two options are highlighted with a red box: "Auto load last profile on startup" and "Auto save profile on exit." The menu also includes options for saving and loading profiles, general settings, display settings, system messages, and other configurations. The interface appears to be related to a navigation or control system, possibly for aviation or simulation purposes, as indicated by terms like "airports/runways," "sector ownership setup," and "aircraft around planes." The top part of the interface shows a time stamp (18:51:21) and other numerical indicators.' If you would like to open a different profile over the time or you have some problems with different views (e.g. you have choosen the "wrong" profile), it's highly recommended to disable the "Auto load last profile on startup" and "Auto save profile on exit" items to

have some problems with different views (e.g. you have choosen the "wrong" profile), it's highly recommended to disable the "Auto load last profile on startup" and "Auto save profile on exit" items to always select the profile manually. You can find these options at OTHER SET at the top menu bar of Euroscope. Login as Observer You can always login as observer (OBS). Open your profile of choice and click on "Connect" at the upper left corner. As Callsign we suggest to use XX_OBS with XX replaced by your initials (the_OBS at the end is required). metadata.abstract: Euroscope is a powerful software used by Air Traffic Controllers (ATC) on the VATSIM network. Proper setup is crucial for effective controlling. The recommended version for use in Germany is 3.2.3.2, as newer versions have caused issues. Installation requires downloading the Visual C++ Redistributable x86 and the Euroscope setup file. After installation, users need to download sectorfiles and plugins from files.aero-nav.com/EDXX, organizing them in a specific folder structure. The software includes various features such as predefined views and airports, and users can select profiles and sector files for different views. For voice communication, the additional software Audio for VATSIM must be installed and configured. Users can log in as observers to listen to other controllers and pilots. It is recommended to manually select profiles to avoid issues with views. The document provides detailed instructions on setting up Euroscope, including downloading necessary files, configuring settings, and using the software effectively.

After installation, users need to download sectorfiles and plugins from files.aero-nav.com/EDXX, organizing them in a specific folder structure. The software includes various features such as predefined views and airports, and users can select profiles and sector files for different views. For voice communication, the additional software Audio for VATSIM must be installed and configured. Users can log in as observers to listen to other controllers and pilots. It is recommended to manually select profiles to avoid issues with views. The document provides detailed instructions on setting up Euroscope, including downloading necessary files, configuring settings, and using the software effectively.

You can find these options at OTHER SET at the top menu bar of Euroscope. Login as Observer You can always login as observer (OBS). Open your profile of choice and click on "Connect" at the upper left corner. As Callsign we suggest to use XX_OBS with XX replaced by your initials (the_OBS at the end is required). Enter your ID and password, check your rating (probably observer), choose your server and you can connect to Vatsim. The interface displays the following elements:

1. **Top Section:**
   - Buttons for "Disconnect" and "Settings."
   - The current transceiver source is "Controller Client."
   - The transceiver count is 1.
   - The ATIS (Automatic Terminal Information Service) source is "Text to Speech from FSD."

2. **Middle Section:**
   - A list of transceivers with their respective frequencies and statuses:
     - **XX_OBS:** Frequency 199.998, status RX (Receive) and TX (Transmit).
     - **EDDF_S_TWR:** Frequency 119.900, status RX (Receive) and XC (Cross Coupled).
     - **EDDF_W_TWR:** Frequency 124.850, status RX (Receive) and XC (Cross Coupled).
   - A button with a "+" symbol, likely for adding new transceivers.

3. **Right Section:**
   - Information about the audio settings for VATSIM V1.5.7.
   - Radio status: TX (Transmit) and RX (Receive).
   - Last received frequency and callsign are not available.
   - An area for "Additional Airport Transceivers" with options to "Add," "Remove All," and "Map."
   - A note indicating that additional transceivers should only be used in exceptional circumstances and advising to contact the division\'s facility engineer for radio coverage issues.

indexed_data.content: Overall, the interface is designed to manage and monitor multiple transceivers for virtual air traffic control operations.' Select the active airport and runways: It is also recommended to activate the airport and it's select runways. Only if the airport is selected, you can see information in the different lists (e.g. you will only see Frankfurt departures in the departliste list, if EDDF is activated). Simply click on the runway symbol at the menu bar at the top, activate the airport for ARR and DEP, chose the runway and you can see everything the controller sees as well. Reset visual point: If you can't see any traffic as Observer even if there should be some, it might be your visual point is to far away from the airport you are looking at. To reposition your center of view, enter .vis into the command line at the bottom and click into the scope. Your center of view is repositioned thereafter.

indexed_data.content:
'The image shows a software interface for connecting to VATSIM (Virtual Air Traffic Simulation Network). The interface is divided into several sections:

1. **Select Connection Mode**: A dropdown menu to choose the connection mode, currently set to "Direct to VATSIM".
2. **Server Connection**: 
   - **Callsign**: Input field with "PGX_OBS".
   - **Real Name**: Input field with "Max Mustermann".
   - **Certificate**: Input field with "123456".
   - **Password**: Input field for a 4-digit password.
   - **Facility**: Dropdown menu set to "Observer".
   - **Rating**: Dropdown menu set to "Observer".
   - **Server**: Dropdown menu set to "GERMANY".
   - **Connect to VATSIM**: Checkbox.
   - **Save Profile** and **Delete Profile**: Buttons for profile management.
3. **Logoff Time**: Input field for logoff time in minutes.
4. **INFO line 1-4**: Input fields for additional information.
5. **Range**: Slider set to 100.
6. **Status**: Status indicator.
7. **Proxy Connection**: 
   - **Server**: Input field set to "localhost".
   - **Status**: Indicator showing "Proxy server is running".
   - **Start Proxy Server** and **Stop Proxy Server**: Buttons to control the proxy server.
8. **Simulator Server**: 
   - **Scenario**: Input field.
   - **Publish simulation data**: Checkbox.
9. **Logging and Playback**: 
   - **Logfile**: Input field with a file path.
   - **Start logging** and **Stop logging**: Buttons to control logging.
   - **Playback**: Controls for playback with buttons for play, pause, stop, and various speed adjustments.

The interface is designed for users to connect to VATSIM, manage their connection settings, and control logging and playback of simulation data.'
